        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The typical line width is about 5-8 km/s, so we need a spectral resolution of at least 1km/s. We have selected two basebands, 2 and 4, with the highest spectral resolution (0.55km/s). These two window contain critical tracers to measure well the kinematics (SO2, CH3CN, SO2) and the temperature (CH3CN) of the disk. Basebands 1 and 3 contain other very important tracers: vibrational HC3N transitions which should be excellent probes (along with H2S) to trace the inner part of the molecular disk; and other SO2 lines needed to have a wide range of excitation energies (37-500K). </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The molecular disk has a diameter of about 1600 AU (Fernandez-Lopez et al. 2011b). The proposed angular resolution, 0.1arcsec or 180AU, is necessary to well resolve the molecular disk.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The SO2 and 34SO2 brightest lines detected at 345 GHz have Tmb of 80 and 10 K, respectively, at an angular resolution of 0.4arcsec ([20], see Figure 2 from this proposal). The selected SO2 and 34SO2 lines have line-strength, Smu^2, and energy levels comparable to those observed with the SMA, so they should have similar line intensities (we have used RADEX adopting the gas volume density, temperature and SO2 column density derived by [13]). We request an rms noise of 2.0 K for a spectral and angular resolutions of 1.0 km/s and 0.1arcsec, respectively. This sensitivity is necessary to detect the 34SO2 lines listed in Table 1 with a signal-to-noise ratio of at least 5 (this isotopologue is partially resolved, so with ALMA the main beam brightness is expected to be larger than the value measured with the SMA). The signal-to-noise ratio for the main SO2 lines will be at least 40. The H2S line should have an intensity similar to the SO2 lines (e.g., [21]), and, thus perfectly detectable. The continuum is expected to be very bright, so we plan to use for self-calibration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
