        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use the standard continuum mode for polarization observations. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Previous observations by Carrasco et al. (2012) has shown that the part of the disk traced by the dust is considerably smaller, 0.15arcsec or 200 AU, than that traced by the molecular lines. In order to properly resolve the dusty disk we request the most extended ALMA configuration available in Band 6, which provides an angular resolution of 0.03arcsec at 263GHz. Selecting 263GHz allows to optimize the angular resolution in Band 6 maintaining the sensitivity and increasing the signal-to-noise ratio of the dust polarization.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Fernandez-Lopez et al. (2011a) measured a flux for the disk of 441 mJy at 220 GHz. The disk has a radius of 0.15arcsec (Carrasco et al. 2012) and a spectral index of 2.5. Therefore we expect a flux of 680 mJy. In order to check the feasibility of the proposed observations we have adopted the disk model with a density profile from Cleeves et al. (2013 ApJ 772, 5) and a temperature profile from Adams et al. (1998, ApJ, 326 865), and scaled it to the size and flux expected for our target at 263 GHz. Then we have included a feasible magnetic field configuration from Padovani et al. (2013, A&amp;A, 560, 114). We used DustPol code from ARTIST (Padovani et al. 2012, 2012, A&amp;A, 543, 16) and the CASA simulator to obtain synthetic dust maps of the Skokes I, Q and U.  To be conservative, we have adopted a dust alignment efficiency about FIVE times lower than the value used in the literature. Under these conditions we detect the polarized signal with a signal-to-noise ratio of ~30. Figure 3 right panel shows a simulation of the disk with the expected 263 GHz flux and size as observed with the proposed angular resolution and sensitivity. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have selected 263 GHz for polarization observations in order to obtain a slighty higher angular resolution and to obtain a better sensitivity for polarized signal withind Band 6.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_NON_STD_CONT_FREQ</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
