    <prp:abstract>HH80-81 represents a unique case where the basic ingredients showing that high-mass protostars form through an accreting disk with a magnetic field are present: A magnetized highly collimated jet; a disk perpendicular to the jet; possible rotating motions of the molecular gas around the massive protostar. There is not any other known massive YSO showing together all these signatures. The goal of this proposal is to confirm and characterize the accretion disk around the powering source of the HH80-81 radio jet, revealing the magtnetic field and the kinematics within the disk. The proposed observations combined with the use of irradiated accretion disk models will allow to unveil the disk and stellar mass, the accretion rate, the disk kinematical behavior and the relevance of the magnetic fields (needed to launch the spectacular jet). Cycle 3 gives the required performance (sensitivity, angular resolution and image fidelity) to unveil for the first time a disk associated with a massive protostar at scales of ~100 AU.</prp:abstract>
